This is the latest development in the investigation launched last month. South Yorkshire Police said they were called at around 9pm on July 26 to the park following reported a young teenage girl had been stabbed. She was taken to a nearby hospital and has since been discharged and is recovering at home. The police have said a 17-year-old boy was arrested on suspicion of affray on Wednesday and has since been bailed with conditions and placed on curfew. Police added they had arrested 13-year-old boy last month on suspicion of attempted murder. He remains on bail as the investigation continues, with police appealing to anyone to come forward with any information about the incident. South Yorkshire Police said in a statement: "Detectives investigating the reported stabbing of a 13-year-old girl in a Sheffield park have made a further arrest. "A 17-year-old boy was arrested on suspicion of affray yesterday (Wednesday 3 August) and has since been bailed with conditions and placed on curfew. "Police were called at around 9pm on Tuesday 26 July to Hillsborough Park following reports a 13-year-old girl had been stabbed. "She was taken to hospital but has since been discharged and is recovering at home. "A 13-year-old boy arrested last month on suspicion of attempted murder remains on bail as the investigation continues. "Officers remain keen to hear from anyone who may hold information about the incident." People can contact the police via its live chat operation, its online portal or by calling 101 quoting incident number 991 of 26 July. Information can also be provided anonymously to independent charity Crimestoppers via their website or by calling their UK contact centre on 0800 555 111.